We do not indeed suppose that all those whom we are addressing are either able or willing to give such prominence to their Latin and Greek studies as will be implied in our treat- ment of this subject. Probably some will not at- tempt to do more than elench the nail which holds this acquisition of their school days. If for the needs of such we seem to be going at too great length into this part of our scheme, we would re- mind them that there are others who are much too good scholars to be content with anything short of a continued and progressive study of classical au- thors, both for their own sake and as the basis of historical or other kindred investigatione or as an instrument of infinite value in the prosecution of the fine arts.
